Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The reports of Ross River virus infections previously this year (2014) have come from Western Australia. The Hunter Valley, Newcastle district is located in New South Wales state, on the east side of Australia. The concern about the risk of increased infection with Ross River virus (RRV) stated this past May of 2014 (see ProMED-mail archive no. 20140509.2462338) has proven justified. RRV has been actively transmitted at above average levels in Western Australia so far in 2014 and now has appeared in the eastern part of the country. RRV transmission to humans, although sporadic in Australia, occurs during the wet season, when vector mosquitoes are abundant. RRV is a zoonotic alphavirus transmitted by a wide range of mosquitoes including _Aedes_ and _Culex_ species. Although not fatal, it causes acute polyarthritis in humans that may persist long after the acute phase of the infection is over. The recommendations to avoid mosquito bites are prudent.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of New South Wales state can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2848232,284. - Mod.TY]
